Markings: The top of the barrel at the receiver is marked “Remington / TRADE MARK” and the left shoulder is marked “.22 SHORT, LONG / OR LONG RIFLE.”. The left lower shoulder is marked “AE” and with an inspection mark. The top of the barrel in front of the rear sight is marked “REMINGTON ARMS – UNION METALLIC CARTRIDGE CO., REMINGTON WORKS, ILION, N.Y. U.S.A. / PEDERSEN’S PATENTS JAN. 5. 1909. OCT. 12. 1909. MAR. 8. 1910. NOV. 21. 1911. APR. 16. 1912.”. The left side of the receiver is marked "MODEL 12 / 838509". When the fire control and stock group are removed from the receiver, visible on the left side is "838509". The underside of the buttplate and the rear face of the stock are marked "84722".Barrel Length: The octagon barrel is 24” in length. Sights / Optics: The front sight is a steel bead dovetailed into the barrel. There is a “V” notched sight dovetailed into the top of the barrel whose elevation is controlled by a screw in the base of the sight. The fire control group/stock assembly is drilled and tapped at the top for a peep sight.Stock Configuration & Condition: The stocks are walnut. The buttstock has a half pistol grip and a crescent shaped blued steel buttplate marked with a “REMINGTON / UMC” logo in an oval. The round forend has 10 grooves, 9 in front of the mounting screw and one behind. The buttstock has darkened with age and oil. There are several small dings and drag lines in the stocks, with a deep bruise on the left of the wrist. The buttstock is slightly shy to the buttplate but fits the receiver well. There are no chips but there is a very small crack at the toe. The LOP measures about 13 1/8” from the front of the trigger to the back of the buttplate, which shows finish loss throughout with light surface oxidation scattered across its face. The buttplate rates in about Good condition. The stocks rate in about Very Good condition as refinished. Type of Finish: Blued Finish Originality: Original Bore Condition: The bore is semi bright with shallow rifling. There is no erosion in the bore.Overall Condition: This rifle retains about 55% of its metal finish. There is thinning at all edges, scattered pinprick erosion. The finish on the barrel is beginning to turn to light patina and there are light marks scattered throughout. The receiver has light scratches scattered throughout, with more concentrated at the seam between the receiver and the fire control group. The magazine tube shows wear from operation. The knurling on the magazine tube rod is worn but well defined. The screw heads are sharp though the slot on the takedown screw is slightly tool marked. The markings are clear. Overall, this rifle rates in about Very Good condition. Mechanics: The action functions correctly. It has a cross-bolt safety at the back of the trigger guard and a slide release at the front of the trigger guard. The action is unique in that the magazine tube moves back and forth with the slide. We have not fired this rifle. As with all used firearms, a thorough cleaning may be necessary to meet your maintenance requirements.Box, Paperwork & Accessories: None

I’m asking $700 for everything which is quite reasonable for a MLE 1892 revolver in the very good condition like this one along with the ammo and holster. title: For Sale:  MR556
postcontent: A direct descendant of the HK416, the MR556A1 is a semi-automatic rifle configuration with match rifle capability developed for civilian users. The MR556A1 uses the HK proprietary gas piston operating system, employing a piston and a solid operating "pusher" rod which virtually eliminates malfunctions common to direct impingement gas systems since hot carbon fouling and waste gases do not enter the receiver area. The HK Modular Rail System (MRS) is truly free-floating for maximum accuracy. The MRS handguard has a more ergonomic design, yet retains many features from the previous FFRS. It uses an HK proprietary keyhole design to allow the attachment of Picatinny rail segments to the handguard. The MR556A1 also has a Picatinny rail machined into the top of its upper receiver for mounting optics and mechanical sights. Major subassemblies, including the upper receiver/barrel assembly, are fully interchangeable with other high quality AR-style firearms. The MR566A1 is produced in the USA from both American and German-made components. The German-made, unchromed barrel is produced by HK's famous cold hammer forging process with the highest quality steel for a barrel that provides superior accuracy and long service life. This model is supplied with one 30-round magazine, a 9" MRS handguard, and Troy Microsights.

postcontent:
CZ P-07 DA/SA .40 S&W with DecockerIncludes 1 spare magazine
Introduced in 2009, the CZ P-07 was the first handgun to feature the convertible Omega trigger system. A simplification of the CZ 75’s hammer ignition method, the Omega’s trigger parts are interlocking in nature, allowing full disassembly and reassembly without the need for gunsmithing experience or tools.
 
The best part of this system is its convertible decocker/safety system. Whether the user wants to carry the pistol cocked and locked like a 1911 or decocked for a double-action first pull of the trigger, a few minutes time allows the swapping of the safety for a decocking lever or vice versa.
 
All sharp edges were removed and a forward cocking serrations and interchangeable backstraps were added. Metal sights, new trigger and hammer designs and a fiber-reinforced polymer rounded out the updates, resulting in a pistol that’s even more comfortable for all-day carry, increasingly adaptable to user preferences and hardier than ever before.

title: For Sale:  Savage 10 FCP-SR Digital Camo
postcontent: This is a hard to find Savage 10 FCP-SR in digital camo (the Savage Manufacturer part number is 19480).  It's chambered in .308/7.62 NATO.  This isn't the new model FCP-SR that's on every shelf in every box store.  Guys who shoot long range know this is a vastly superior build compared to the new model.  I configured this rifle for a long range class I took in Virginia that was taught by Dan Newbury. The rifle features a 24 inch heavy fluted barrel with a muzzle break, a one piece picitinny rail, digital camo AccuStock, AccuTrigger, and an all steel construction 10 round detachable box magazine by Accurate Mag Company.  In addition to that, I have a 6-18 Vortex Crossfire II scope with a level attached, a cheek riser, and an imitation Harris bipod.  I zeroed the rifle at a hundred yards last August, cleaned it, oiled it, and put it away.  The only adjustment I never made to it is on the magazine feed lip.  I never bothered to buy the adjustment tool because I feed the ammo by hand one round at a time when I shoot long range.  The mag feed lip probably needs to be opened up about 3 thousandths or so to get the cartridges to feed more smoothly.  The adjustment tool costs about 25 bucks.If you have any questions, feel free to ask.  If the ad is up, the rifle is still for sale.  1000 dollars gets everything I listed in the ad.  900 gets you everything but the optic.  Not looking for trades at this time.  And thanks for your interest.
